    id: 142, title: "The Ethics of Fashion", topic: "clothing and fashion", level: "B2", wordCount: 451,
    text: `The garment you are wearing right now has a biography. Before it reached your body, it was designed somewhere, the raw material from which it is made was grown or synthesized somewhere else, it was cut and sewn by workers in a factory — most likely in Bangladesh, Vietnam, Cambodia, or another country where labor costs are low — and it travelled, probably by ship, across one or more oceans. Each stage of this journey has an environmental footprint and involves human labor whose conditions vary enormously. When we buy a piece of clothing for five euros, we are purchasing the output of this entire chain. The question of what we owe to the people and environments involved is one that most of us find easier to avoid than to answer.

The scale of the fashion industry makes this avoidance understandable but increasingly difficult to sustain. Fashion is the second most polluting industry in the world after oil. The production of synthetic fibers releases petrochemicals into waterways. Cotton, one of the world's most widely grown crops, is one of its most pesticide-intensive. The dyeing and finishing of fabrics is responsible for approximately twenty percent of the world's clean water pollution. These are not peripheral effects of an otherwise benign industry; they are structural features of how clothes are produced at the scale the market demands.

The human dimension is equally difficult to look away from. The death of over 1,100 workers in the collapse of the Rana Plaza factory complex in Dhaka in 2013 created a brief global reckoning with the conditions in which most of the world's clothing is produced. In the years since, there have been improvements in safety inspections at some factories and some consolidation of supply chain transparency commitments among major brands. But the economic logic that produces poverty wages, excessive working hours, union suppression, and dangerous conditions — the need to produce ever more at ever lower cost — has not fundamentally changed.

Consumer responses to these realities exist on a spectrum. At one end is deliberate ignorance: the choice not to investigate too closely, to treat clothing as a disposable consumer category, and to take advantage of the extraordinarily low prices that the current system makes possible. At the other end is the kind of comprehensive ethical audit of one's own wardrobe that requires significant time, money, and information that most people do not have access to.

Between these extremes, a more realistic and arguably more honest position acknowledges the structural nature of the problem — that individual consumer choices, while not irrelevant, cannot resolve a systemic issue that requires regulatory intervention at the level of trade law, labor rights, and environmental standards. This does not mean individual choices are meaningless. It means that treating them as the primary solution is a form of moral convenience that lets governments and corporations off the hook.`
