    id: 145, title: "The Green Revolution and Its Aftermath", topic: "agriculture and farming", level: "B2", wordCount: 454,
    text: `In the decades following World War Two, the world faced what many observers considered an imminent catastrophe. Global population was growing rapidly, and projections suggested that food production could not keep pace. Famine on a massive scale seemed possible, perhaps inevitable.

What followed instead was the Green Revolution — a transformation of agricultural productivity achieved through the development and widespread adoption of high-yielding crop varieties, synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, and irrigation. Beginning in Mexico in the 1940s and 1950s under the direction of agronomist Norman Borlaug, the approach spread to South Asia, sub-Saharan Africa, and beyond. Between 1960 and 1990, global cereal production doubled. The worst predictions of mass famine did not materialize. Borlaug received the Nobel Peace Prize in 1970.

The achievements of the Green Revolution were real and substantial. It saved hundreds of millions of lives. But its costs and limitations — inadequately acknowledged at the time and in much subsequent popular discussion — were also real and substantial, and they continue to shape the agricultural challenges of the present.

The high-yielding varieties that drove the revolution were not well adapted to the conditions of all regions, and required reliable irrigation, fertilizer inputs, and pest management to achieve their potential. In regions with variable rainfall, poor soils, or limited access to inputs, the benefits were uneven. The focus on a small number of high-yielding varieties also accelerated the loss of genetic diversity in crop plants — traditional varieties that had been selected over millennia for local adaptability were abandoned and often lost.

The intensive use of synthetic nitrogen fertilizer, while dramatically increasing yields, created its own environmental cascade. Nitrogen runoff from agricultural land is a leading cause of aquatic dead zones — regions of ocean so depleted of oxygen by algal blooms fed by fertilizer runoff that they cannot support marine life. The Haber-Bosch process, by which synthetic nitrogen is produced, accounts for roughly two percent of global energy consumption and a significant proportion of greenhouse gas emissions.

The social consequences were also mixed. The capital-intensive nature of Green Revolution agriculture favored larger landowners who could afford inputs and irrigation. In some regions, the transformation accelerated the displacement of small farmers and contributed to rural-to-urban migration.

These critiques do not negate the revolution's achievements. They do, however, complicate any simple narrative of technological salvation and suggest that the agricultural challenges of the current era — feeding a growing population while reversing the environmental damage of the past century — will require approaches that are simultaneously more productive and more ecologically sophisticated. What worked once, under one set of conditions, with a particular understanding of costs and benefits, is not a template that can be straightforwardly applied again.`
