    id: 147, title: "The Financialization of Everything", topic: "business and money", level: "B2", wordCount: 449,
    text: `Over the past four decades, a transformation has occurred in the structure of advanced economies that has been variously described, analyzed, and contested but is rarely given a single coherent name in public discourse. The transformation is this: an ever-larger proportion of economic activity — and of the profits generated by that activity — has migrated from the production of goods and services toward the management of financial assets. Economists call this process "financialization," and its consequences pervade almost every aspect of contemporary economic and social life.

The most immediate manifestation is the growth of the financial sector itself. In the United States, financial services accounted for approximately ten percent of corporate profits in 1950. By the 2000s, that figure had risen to approximately forty percent, even as the sector employed a relatively small proportion of the total workforce and produced no physical goods. This expansion was driven by deregulation, by the invention of increasingly complex financial instruments, by the globalization of capital flows, and by the intellectual prestige of economic theories that treated financial markets as efficient allocators of resources.

But financialization extends beyond the financial sector into the behavior of companies in other sectors. The rise of "shareholder value" as the dominant framework for corporate governance encouraged managers to prioritize short-term returns to shareholders over long-term investment in productive capacity, workforce development, and research. Companies began directing a larger share of their profits toward share buybacks and dividends — which boost shareholder returns — rather than toward capital investment. This pattern is associated with the erosion of manufacturing capacity in several high-income countries.

Housing, education, healthcare, and infrastructure have all undergone varying degrees of financialization — coming to be treated less as social goods and more as financial assets or investment vehicles. This shift has profound implications for access and affordability. When housing is primarily an asset class, the interests of investors and those of residents seeking shelter are in direct tension. When student debt is securitized and sold to investors, the financial interests in maintaining high tuition levels acquire additional institutional weight.

The political economy of financialization is deeply entangled with the rise of inequality in high-income countries. The ownership of financial assets is highly concentrated; as the financial sector's share of the economy has grown, so have the incomes and wealth of those who own substantial quantities of financial assets. The erosion of labor's bargaining power — through deindustrialization, weakened union rights, and the growing use of automation and contract labor — is in part a consequence of the same structural shifts.

None of this implies that finance itself is parasitic or harmful. Credit markets, insurance, and efficient allocation of investment capital are genuine contributions to economic welfare. The question is one of proportion, governance, and the distribution of the gains — questions that are, in the end, political rather than purely economic.`
