    id: 151, title: "Populism and the Crisis of Liberal Democracy", topic: "politics and society", level: "B2", wordCount: 451,
    text: `Liberal democracy — a system combining democratic elections with constitutional protections for individual rights, the rule of law, and the independence of institutions — has been the dominant political framework of wealthy nations for most of the past century. Its foundations were shaken by the catastrophes of totalitarianism in the twentieth century, but it emerged from those challenges strengthened, spreading to new regions as former dictatorships and communist states transitioned toward democratic governance. By the end of the twentieth century, the political scientist Francis Fukuyama was prepared to argue that liberal democracy represented the "end of history" — the final form of human political organization.

The first decades of the twenty-first century have severely complicated this confidence. Across diverse contexts — in Hungary and Poland in Europe, in Brazil, in India, and most prominently in the United States — political movements typically described as populist have achieved power while challenging institutional norms that liberal democracy depends upon: the independence of courts and media, the integrity of electoral processes, protections for minority rights, and the legitimacy of political opposition.

Populism is a notoriously difficult concept to define precisely, partly because movements described as populist vary greatly in their specific programs and ideologies. What they typically share is a rhetorical structure that divides society between a virtuous and culturally homogeneous "people" and a corrupt, alien, or parasitic "elite," and that claims to express the authentic will of the people against the machinations of this elite. This structure is inherently anti-pluralist: it treats political opposition and institutional constraints as illegitimate interference with the popular will rather than as features of a well-functioning democratic system.

The causes of populism's current resurgence are themselves disputed, but several candidate explanations have significant empirical support. The economic dislocations produced by globalization and technological change have left large communities with a well-grounded sense that the political mainstream failed to represent their interests or acknowledge their losses. The hollowing out of intermediate civic institutions — trade unions, local political parties, religious organizations — has removed the structures through which diverse interests were historically aggregated and represented. Cultural and demographic change has created anxieties about identity and belonging that mainstream politics has been ill-equipped to address.

Understanding populism as a symptom rather than simply a cause — as evidence of genuine failures within liberal democratic systems that need to be addressed rather than simply pathologies to be overcome — is difficult for those who identify with the institutions under challenge. But it is probably the more honest and ultimately more useful analytical starting point.

Liberal democracy faces a genuine test. Its defense requires not only institutional resilience but a serious reckoning with the conditions that made its challengers appear credible to so many of its own citizens.`
